<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-08-29T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-08-29T16:00:00-05:00" n="717" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d717">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.50 Am 3/6: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-08-29T17:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">August 29,
                                        1922—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>115. Our 102 of July 24, 4 p.m. Department now believes that although we
                            should be ready to make an impartial economic investigation at any time
                            when it may appear feasible, the better way would be not to press the
                            matter at present but to let the proposal come from the Moscow
                            authorities. Then we can make our conditions.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>